{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01PhmAsB3ht2SMmU1mEyhur7","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a comprehensive understanding. Let me also check the embeddings file quickly.\n\nThe current state:\n- Iteration 4: 50% accuracy (3/6 passing: ARAYES SHRAK, MIXED SEED CRISPBREAD, OVERNIGHT STRAIGHT PIZZA DOUGH)\n- 3 failures remaining: Baked Eggs, FINNISH FLATBREADS, SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS\n\nThe iteration 3 improvement plan proposed 3 changes. Looking at the current code (iteration 4), I can see what was implemented:\n1. The `isStructuralHeading` was refactored to filter insignificant tokens (sigWords filter)\n\n\n2. The `firstStructuralHeading` continuation logic was added to handle multi-line headings\n3. `baseScore` was introduced with a threshold using `bestBaseScore * 0.7` to be more selective\n4. A pre-filter removes word-boundary prefixes of firstStructuralHeading before deduplication\n5. However, the dedup logic still relies on \"shorter wins\" with a guard comment preventing changes, so the strategy was to filter prefixes upstream rather than modify the dedup itself—this partially worked by fixing ARAYES but left three recipes still failing.\n\nLooking at the remaining failures, I can see the core issues: Baked Eggs has no structural heading to filter on, FINNISH's threshold is still too aggressive despite baseScore adjustments, and SAFFRON has OCR garbage incorrectly claiming the structural heading while the correct join gets removed. The pre-filter approach only addresses cases where firstStructuralHeading exists and matches, so I need a more comprehensive fix that handles all three scenarios. The garbage text passes the structural heading check because it appears earlier in the document, gets the structural bonus, and then the dedup logic removes the actual correct title since it's a longer version of an earlier candidate. So I'm dealing with two separate problems compounding: the structural heading detection is too permissive, and the dedup is too aggressive with substring matching.\n\nFor the baked eggs issue, I think the cleanest approach is to extend the pre-filter to recognize when a longer candidate is built by joining lines that start with continuation characters like &, /, or +. If that pattern exists, I should protect the full join from being deduplicated away by its first-line component.\n\nFor the Finnish title problem, the threshold is just too low to catch the second all-caps variant.  The first heading gets a structural bonus that pushes its threshold up to `rawScore * 0.7 + 0.126`, which means the second heading needs a raw score above 0.153 to qualify—but it's falling short of that.\n\nThe feedback hints that the real issue is the structural bonus being exclusive to the first heading. If I applied the structural bonus to all qualifying headings instead of just the first one, both Finnish titles would get the same +0.10 boost and wouldn't have this unfair gap between them. I'm considering whether to expand the structural bonus eligibility to all candidates that pass the structural heading check, rather than limiting it to just the first match.\n\nFor the OCR garbage problem, the fragment \"FRON WHEAT BUNS\" passes all the structural checks even though it's clearly truncated. I could add a word validity check—if the first word of a structural heading candidate isn't a real English word, it probably shouldn't qualify as a legitimate heading.\n\nBut there's a better approach: instead of always picking the first structural heading, I should pick the one with the highest embedding score. The complete, correct title would naturally embed better against the reference than a truncated OCR artifact, so this would elegantly handle both the truncation issue and cases where multiple structural candidates exist.\n\nThe challenge is that structural heading selection happens before embedding scores are computed, so I'd need to restructure the pipeline to validate candidates against their scores. Alternatively, I could move the structural heading selection to after scoring, or at least gate it with embedding validation.\n\nActually, thinking through the feedback more carefully: the continuation-aware pre-filter fix would already help with part of the SAFFRON problem, and applying the structural bonus to all structural headings (not just the first) would fix the FINNISH case. For SAFFRON specifically, the correct multi-line join needs to survive dedup and outscore the garbled fragment—if I give the structural bonus to all candidates, then the complete title should win out.\n\nBut a more targeted approach might be better: keep the continuation-aware pre-filter to protect joins from dedup, then add a truncation detector for structural headings that flags suspicious fragments like \"FRON\"—words that don't appear to be complete English words and could be suffix fragments.\n\nThe challenge is detecting truncation reliably. \"FRON\" is suspicious because it's not a common word, but it's 4 letters long so it passes basic length checks. A better heuristic might be checking if a candidate appears as a suffix of another candidate in the same set—if \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS\" and \"FRON WHEAT BUNS\" both exist, the latter is likely a garbled version of the former.\n\nLooking at the actual feedback, both \"FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)\" at line 29 and \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\" at line 54 are present in the OCR input, so there's real overlap to work with here.\n\nRather than trying to detect garbling upfront, I could defer the structural heading selection until after scoring. The idea is to score all candidates first without any structural bonus, then among those that pass the structural heading check, pick the highest-scoring one and apply the bonus retroactively. This way \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\" would naturally rank higher than \"FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)\" because it embeds better as an actual title.\n\nThe tradeoff is that for cases like FINNISH, if I apply the structural bonus to all qualifying headings, both titles get boosted, but if I keep it as a single best-scoring structural heading, the threshold issue comes back. I need to think through the overall strategy more carefully. One approach is to add continuation-aware multi-line join protection before dedup—if a multi-line join has a continuation character at the start of the second part, I can remove the first-line prefix from the selected candidates to prevent false splits.\n\nFor the structural bonus itself, applying it to all candidates that pass the structural heading check would help cases like FINNISH where multiple titles exist, but it risks making the bonus equivalent to just increasing the all-caps bonus. The structural check is stricter though—it requires at least two significant words with four or more letters each, versus just four letters total for all-caps.\n\nModifying the code to award the bonus to any candidate meeting the structural criteria would equalize both FINNISH titles and boost legitimate headings like \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK,\" though it would also catch some false positives like \"FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1).\"\n\nFor the continuation logic, the issue is that it anchors to the first structural heading by position, which fails when that heading is garbage. I could either restructure the pipeline to score headings first and use the best-scoring one as the anchor, or compute continuation joins for all structural headings upfront and mark which ones have valid continuations.\n\nLooking at the SAFFRON case more carefully: the first structural heading is \"FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)\" from the previous recipe, so no continuation is found for it. But the real title starts at line 54 with \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\" and continues on line 55, which should be detected as a 2-line join. The fix is to check all structural headings for continuations, not just the first one. The join passes the structural heading check since it has enough significant words with adequate length, so it gets both the structural bonus and all-caps bonus for a total of +0.18, matching what \"FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)\" receives—but the join should win because it has better embedding similarity as an actual title. Now I need to make sure the continuation pre-filter properly handles this case without breaking the deduplication logic.\n\nI'm redesigning the pre-filter to be more general: instead of just checking prefixes of the first structural heading, I'll detect any multi-line join by finding candidates where another candidate's text is a strict word-boundary prefix and the remainder starts with a continuation character, then remove the shorter prefix candidate to protect the join.\n\nWriting the filter logic...\n\nThis approach removes first-line fragments whenever a continuation join exists, handling cases like \"Baked Eggs (& Coriander)\" and \"SAFFRON (/ COTTAGE CHEESE)\" regardless of heading type. The risk of being too aggressive is minimal since it only triggers when a shorter candidate is a word-boundary prefix of a longer one that continues with a joining character—a pretty specific pattern that shouldn't accidentally remove legitimate shorter titles.\n\nLet me verify this doesn't break the Pierogi Ruskie case: \"200g\" doesn't start with any joining character, so the filter doesn't apply and the existing dedup preserves \"Pierogi Ruskie\" correctly. Now I'm checking whether adding a structural bonus to all headings in Change 2 could introduce regressions, particularly with cases like ARAYES SHRAK where the firstStructuralHeading is the join itself.\n\nFor ARAYES SHRAK, neither individual part qualifies as a structural heading since they're single words, so only the join gets the bonus—no change in behavior. MIXED SEED CRISPBREAD and OVERNIGHT STRAIGHT PIZZA DOUGH are already single structural headings that get the bonus, and any other ALL_CAPS candidates would need to also outscore them on embedding similarity to cause issues, which is unlikely. For FINNISH, both titles receive the same +0.10 bonus, so I need to check their base scores to see if the ranking shifts. Both \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)\" and \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\" pass the structural heading check since all their significant words meet the length threshold, earning them each the +0.10 bonus. Now I'm checking how the pre-filtering affects these candidates. The issue is that giving all headings a structural bonus actually makes things worse—it keeps both the garbled fragment and the correct title. I need to eliminate the corrupted version. The most promising approach is overlap detection: if two candidates share significant word overlap, they're likely OCR variants of the same title, so I should keep the one with the higher embedding score. For the SAFFRON example, \"FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)\" and \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\" share \"WHEAT BUNS,\" so I'd prefer the more complete version based on embedding quality.\n\nActually, a cleaner solution might be to restructure the pipeline entirely: instead of applying bonuses to all structural headings, I'll score all candidates first, then select only the highest-scoring structural heading as the firstStructuralHeading. This means building candidates, computing raw scores, picking the best structural candidate, extending it with continuation logic, and then applying bonuses afterward.\n\nThis should fix the SAFFRON case—the full title would outscore the fragment and get selected. But for FINNISH, both titles score similarly, so the first one by position still wins and the second still falls below threshold. I need a separate approach for that: maybe excluding the structural bonus from the threshold calculation itself.\n\nI'm computing the threshold using only raw embedding scores and the all-caps bonus, leaving out structural and position bonuses. This way the threshold reflects baseline title-likeness rather than getting inflated by bonuses meant to break ties. For FINNISH specifically, both titles would have similar raw scores plus the all-caps bonus, so they'd both clear a threshold that isn't artificially raised by the structural bonus on the first one.\n\nNow looking at SAFFRON, the first structural heading gets the structural bonus while the second gets only the all-caps bonus, which should differentiate them properly.\n\nBut the real issue is that \"FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)\" passes the threshold checks because it genuinely looks like a valid title from an embedding standpoint—it contains real food terminology. The multi-title guard doesn't help either since both fragments are in all caps. I need to find a way to detect and filter out this truncated fragment specifically, since the scoring system alone won't catch it. as OCR garbage. Let me think...\n\nOne approach: detect that a structural heading candidate overlaps significantly with another candidate. If \"FRON WHEAT BUNS\" shares 2+ content words with \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS\", and the second one is longer/more complete, the first might be a garbled duplicate.\n\nBut this is complex and brittle. Let me think about what other signal we can use.\n\nActually - \"FRON\" is not a real word. In the context of recipe titles, we could check if the first word of a candidate appears to be a truncated word. Signs of truncation:\n- Starts with an unusual consonant cluster (FR is fine actually... \"from\" starts with \"fr\")\n- Actually \"FRON\" could be \"from\" misspelled. It's hard to detect.\n\nWait - the feedback mentions that the algorithm \"has no mechanism to prefer later structural headings over earlier ones when the earlier one is garbled.\" What if I use position relative to the recipe body instead? Recipe titles typically appear just before the ingredients and instructions start, so I could detect where the recipe body begins and infer that the title is the structural heading closest to and immediately preceding that content. For the SAFFRON example, line 54 \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\" comes right before the recipe body text, whereas line 29's garbled version is earlier in the document, so I'd prioritize the later, cleaner heading.\n\nBut this adds complexity. Let me step back and look at the three failures more carefully - they have different root causes. For the garbled fragment issue specifically, instead of trying to detect OCR errors directly, I could make the multi-title guard smarter by checking if candidates overlap significantly in content, and preferring the longer or more complete version. keeps all of them. What if we add a \"duplicate title detector\" that recognizes when two ALL_CAPS candidates are likely garbled versions of the same recipe and merges/deduplicates them?\n\nFor SAFFRON: \"FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)\" and \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\" — detecting these as related requires fuzzy string matching, which is complex.\n\nAlternatively, what if we check word overlap between ALL_CAPS candidates? If candidate A shares >50% of its content words with candidate B, they might be duplicates.\n\n\"FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)\" content words: FRON, WHEAT, BUNS, VARIATION, 1\n\"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\" content words: SAFFRON, WHEAT, BUNS, WITH, QUARK, COTTAGE, CHEESE, VARIATION, D\n\nShared: WHEAT, BUNS, VARIATION (3 words)\nA has 5 words, overlap is 3/5 = 60%\nB has 9 words, overlap is 3/9 = 33%\n\nUsing the overlap from A's perspective (60% > 50%), we could flag this as a duplicate and keep the higher-scoring one. This approach seems workable — I'd formalize it as a pairwise word overlap check across ALL_CAPS candidates, flagging anything above 50% threshold from the shorter candidate's perspective as a likely duplicate, then retaining whichever has the better score.\n\nTesting this on FINNISH: \"FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS\" vs \"FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS\" share FINNISH and FLATBREADS, giving 2/3 = 67% overlap, which would correctly identify them as distinct recipes despite the high overlap.\n\nWait, that's the problem — this approach would incorrectly flag them as duplicates when they're actually two separate titles on the same page. The word overlap method can't distinguish between a garbled duplicate and two genuinely different recipes that happen to share common words.\n\nThe real difference is that SAFFRON's garbled version comes from a different recipe entirely, while FINNISH's two titles are both legitimate and on the same page. I need a way to detect when candidates are actually corrupted versions of each other rather than just similar-sounding titles.\n\nMaybe I should lean more heavily on the embedding similarity score instead of relying on word overlap heuristics.\n\nActually, thinking about this more carefully—with MiniLM embeddings, even a garbled fragment like \"FRON WHEAT BUNS\" would probably score well because the model picks up on the food-related terms, so it won't naturally filter out these corrupted candidates.\n\nI think the best path forward is to make the firstStructuralHeading selection score-gated and then handle the multi-title problem as a separate concern. Let me map out the approach: I'd add continuation-aware protection for multi-line joins that start with special characters like &, /, +, or :.  Then I'd restructure the heading selection to pick the highest-scoring structural heading rather than just the first one, removing the prefix before deduplication. Finally, I'd exclude the structuralBonus from the threshold calculation so it doesn't artificially raise the bar for other candidates. This combination should let the real title win in SAFFRON while keeping the second title viable in FINNISH and preserving the Baked Eggs join. Both survive the multi-title guard since there are at least two all-caps options, keeping \"FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS\". For the saffron case, I'm checking whether the join candidate qualifies as a structural heading and could be selected as the firstStructuralHeading—if it does, it would receive the structural bonus and likely become the highest-scoring option.\n\nLooking at the saffron scenario more carefully: the join passes through the pre-filter and dedup checks, and both it and the garbage fragment survive as all-caps candidates, resulting in the wrong output again. The real issue is that the garbage fragment keeps passing all the heuristic checks despite being clearly wrong, so I need a stronger filtering mechanism to catch these cases.\n\nLet me examine whether the garbled detection function would actually catch \"FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)\" by checking its vowel ratio and other characteristics.\n\nLooking at the findBurstEnd logic...\n\nContinuing with the code description...\n\nThe function scans through lines until it hits one that's either 20+ characters long or doesn't match the garbled pattern, then returns that position. So for the SAFFRON case, the burst of garbled OCR artifacts from the previous page would end once we reach a legitimate line like \"FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS\" at line 16, meaning lines 1-15 get flagged as the burst and anything after that position is considered clean content. Looking at how `isLikelyGarbled` evaluates \"BUNS\" — it has enough letters, a decent vowel ratio, and doesn't trigger the orphan word check, so it returns false. This means `findBurstEnd` wouldn't skip past line 1, stopping right there instead of filtering out the garbled content.\n\nSo \"FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)\" at line 29 becomes a valid candidate with no positional way to exclude it. Rather than trying to filter it out, I should recognize that a single recipe page should only have one title — and when there are multiple ALL_CAPS heading candidates, the duplicate one is likely OCR bleed from an adjacent page. I could build a detector that identifies suspicious duplicates by comparing candidates and flagging ones that appear to be fragments or variations of each other.\n\nLooking at the actual word overlap: SAFFRON's candidates share WHEAT, BUNS, and VARIATION (75% of the shorter candidate's significant words), while FINNISH's candidates share FINNISH and FLATBREADS. This pattern of high word overlap suggests the shorter candidate is probably noise rather than a legitimate alternative title.\n\nBut there's something more telling here: \"FRON\" in the SAFFRON candidate looks like it could be a truncation of \"SAFFRON\" itself, whereas \"MILK\" and \"POTATO\" in the FINNISH candidates are complete, distinct words. So I should check whether non-shared words in the shorter candidate are actually suffixes of words in the longer candidate—if \"FRON\" matches the last 4 characters of \"SAFFRON,\" that's a strong signal of truncation rather than a genuine variant.\n\nTesting this logic: \"RYE BREAD\" versus \"SOURDOUGH RYE BREAD\" wouldn't trigger this because both words are shared. But \"OATS BREAD\" versus \"SOATS BREAD\" is trickier—\"OATS\" isn't technically a suffix of \"SOATS,\" though there's clearly something garbled happening there.\n\nI think checking for substrings instead of just suffixes makes more sense. So if a non-shared word from the shorter candidate appears as a substring within a longer word from the longer candidate, and there's at least a 2-character length difference, that's a strong signal of truncation or corruption.\n\nBut this approach is getting complicated and brittle. Let me reconsider the core problem differently—maybe I'm overcomplicating the SAFFRON case. The real issue is that OCR bleeding created two recipe titles on the same page, and I should focus on identifying which one is the primary recipe by looking at which title has more recipe content following it. one has recipe body content (ingredients, instructions) following it. The title that's immediately followed by recipe content is the primary title.\n\nActually, this is hard to implement without significant changes. Let me think of something simpler.\n\nLet me look at it from a practical standpoint. The expected output for SAFFRON is just the full title: \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK : COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\". (Note: the expected output uses \" : \" as separator, but the OCR has \" / \". The test harness probably normalizes this.)\n\nWhat if the approach is:\n1. Fix the dedup/continuation issue so the correct join survives (Changes 1)\n2. Use score-gated structural heading (Change 2)  \n3. Exclude structural bonus from threshold (Change 3)\n4. Add a heuristic in the multi-title guard:\n\nI'm wondering if I should check for OCR truncation when multiple ALL_CAPS candidates have significant word overlap—if a shorter candidate contains words that appear to be substrings of words in the longer one, it's probably noise and should be filtered out. But actually, let me step back. The embedding scores should naturally favor the complete, meaningful title over the truncated one. \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE\" has real food vocabulary and grammatical coherence, while \"FRON WHEAT BUNS\" is clearly corrupted, so MiniLM should score the full version much higher against the reference.\n\nIf the score difference is substantial enough, the garbled fragment might fall below the threshold naturally once I exclude the structural bonus from the calculation. With real embeddings, this difference could be significant, though I can't guarantee it with mock data in testing.\n\nI think the pragmatic approach is to focus on the definite bugs first—the dedup issue that kills joins and the threshold problem that excludes second titles—then propose a reasonable heuristic for OCR noise while acknowledging where real-world embedding behavior will help versus where I'll need additional rules.\n\nLooking back at the expected output, I notice the OCR has \"/\" but the expected shows \":\", which might just be how the original recipe is formatted. The key issue is that the current output is severely truncated, losing most of the title. Rather than trying to perfectly handle SAFFRON as a primary goal, I should focus on reliably fixing Baked Eggs and FINNISH first, then treat SAFFRON improvements as a stretch goal once the core issues are resolved.\n\nFor a cleaner approach to OCR deduplication, I'm thinking about checking pairs of ALL_CAPS candidates after the multi-title guard produces its final list. I'd compute Jaccard similarity of their significant words—those with at least 4 alphabetic characters—and if the similarity exceeds 0.4, treat them as likely OCR duplicates and keep the one with the higher score. This would catch cases like \"FRON WHEAT BUNS VARIATION 1\" versus \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK COTTAGE CHEESE VARIATION\" where the first is clearly a corrupted version of the second.\n\nActually, Jaccard similarity might be too strict here—the intersection-to-union ratio doesn't capture the right relationship when one string is a substring of another. I'm switching to a containment ratio instead, which measures what fraction of the shorter candidate's significant words appear in the longer one. That gives me 0.75 for the SAFFRON example, which feels more appropriate for detecting OCR corruption. Let me check how this works for the FINNISH cases too.\n\nFor FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS versus FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS, the containment is 0.67—both are high, so I need another signal. I'm thinking about adding a substring check: if the non-shared words in the shorter candidate are substrings of words in the longer candidate, that's a red flag for OCR errors. FRON is clearly part of SAFFRON, so that would flag it as a duplicate. Now I need to verify whether MILK appears as a substring anywhere in the FINNISH POTATO version.\n\nI'm formalizing this into a rule: two candidates are likely duplicates if they share more than 50% of their significant words AND every non-shared word from the shorter candidate appears as a substring within the longer candidate's words. Let me test this against edge cases to make sure it holds up. The empty set case would actually get caught by regular deduplication already, so that's not a real concern. Let me test this logic against a legitimate non-duplicate pair like \"CHOCOLATE CHIP COOKIES\" versus \"CHOCOLATE COOKIES WITH FROSTING\"—they share enough words to pass the threshold, but CHIP isn't a substring of any word in the second recipe, so it wouldn't incorrectly flag as an OCR duplicate.\n\nNow with \"BREAD ROLLS\" versus \"SOURDOUGH BREAD ROLLS WITH SEEDS,\" the shorter recipe has no unique words, so the substring check vacuously passes and it gets flagged as a duplicate—which seems right since one is clearly just an elaboration of the other.\n\nBut here's the tension: if I apply the continuation pre-filter from Change 1, it would remove the shorter one before dedup even runs. Without that pre-filter, regular dedup would remove the longer one instead, which is backwards. So the pre-filter actually fixes this case, but only if the longer title is genuinely a continuation join rather than a completely separate recipe.\n\nThe OCR duplicate detector would catch this scenario, but it's risky since it relies on substring matching. Let me think through the SAFFRON case again with all three proposed changes applied together to see how they interact. I'm checking whether that \"/\" prefix actually triggers the garbled text filter—it doesn't match the lowercase letter pattern, and the multi-word check also skips it since \"/\" isn't alphabetic. So it should pass the hard filters. Now moving into the scoring phase with the new score-gated structural heading approach.\n\nI'm computing raw scores for all candidates by embedding them and comparing against references, then filtering for structural headings. The top candidates like \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\" and \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\" both qualify as structural headings since they have multiple significant words that meet the length threshold.\n\nNow I'm checking which one has the highest raw score to select as the final heading. The join candidate should have the highest raw score, making its threshold score the baseline at join_rawScore + 0.08 multiplied by 0.7. For \"FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)\" to pass this threshold, its raw score plus the all-caps bonus needs to meet or exceed that cutoff, but if the join's raw score is significantly higher, the fragment could get filtered out. I need to check the actual test fixture to see whether the mock embeddings would cause both candidates to match the same title words.\n\nLooking at the real integration tests with actual MiniLM embeddings against OCR text files, \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\" should score noticeably higher than the garbled fragment since SAFFRON, QUARK, and COTTAGE CHEESE are legitimate food terms that the embeddings would recognize. This difference might be enough to push the garbled version below the threshold, though I can't be completely certain without running it. I should also consider adding OCR duplicate detection as a safety mechanism and check whether the pre-filter for firstStructuralHeading already handles the SAFFRON case.\n\nThe pre-filter logic removes candidates that are space-delimited prefixes of the first structural heading, but in this scenario it's checking whether the heading itself starts with a candidate's text — which won't catch the SAFFRON case since the full heading is what we're comparing against. the threshold. With Changes 2 and 3, the join gets the highest score from its structural bonus and all-caps bonus combined with a strong raw score, while the threshold itself is calculated without the structural bonus. So the garbled fragment only passes if its score—which includes the all-caps bonus but no structural bonus, adjusted by its position factor—exceeds that threshold. Given the fragment's position around 41% through the document, I'm working out whether its adjusted score clears this bar.\n\nThe real question is whether the actual embedding scores will make this work, and since that's uncertain, I'm planning to add an OCR duplicate detector as a safety mechanism. I'm also checking the expected output for the SAFFRON case—the test expects \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK : COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\", but the OCR text has a \"/\" instead of a \":\". I need to verify what the results file actually shows.\n\nNow I'm putting together the improvement plan with four key changes: making the join protection aware of continuation lines, gating structural heading selection by score, excluding the structural bonus from the threshold calculation, and adding OCR duplicate detection as a fallback.\n\nFor the score-gated structural heading approach, I'm reconsidering the implementation. Rather than restructuring the entire scoring loop, I can keep the positional selection but add validation afterward. Actually, a cleaner approach is to run scoring once without the structural bonus, then identify the best-scoring structural heading based on that initial pass, and apply the bonus selectively. This way the scoring loop runs just once with the core factors, and I pick the structural heading that performs best before adding the bonus.\n\nNow I'm thinking about the SAFFRON case more carefully. Beyond score-gating the structural heading, I could add a heuristic that checks whether an ALL_CAPS heading is preceded by clean recipe text versus garbled content—that context might help distinguish the real title from false positives.\n\nBut actually, looking at what comes *after* the heading might be more reliable. A genuine recipe title is usually followed by subtitle text or metadata patterns like SERVES or PREP TIME, whereas garbled text or recipe body would follow a false positive. So I could check the lines immediately after each candidate heading to strengthen the signal.\n\nThis is getting complicated though. Let me step back and focus on the four changes I've identified: continuation-aware join protection, score-gated structural headings, structural-bonus-free thresholds, and OCR duplicate detection. These should collectively handle all three failure cases without needing overly complex heuristics.\n\nFor the OCR duplicate check specifically, I can apply it after the multi-title guard when I have the final candidates, checking each ALL_CAPS pair against the duplicate rule and removing suspected duplicates if triggered.\n\nActually, I'm reconsidering whether I even need the OCR duplicate detection. If the score-gated structural heading change works correctly, the joined text gets a structural bonus that should push it above the garbled fragment's score, and the structural-bonus-free threshold ensures the fragment can't win on raw score alone. So the combination of those changes might be sufficient without needing the duplicate detection step.\n\nBut looking at the multi-title guard logic, if both the join and the garbled fragment end up in the selected list and both are ALL_CAPS, they'd both be kept since the condition checks for two or more ALL_CAPS candidates. The expected output for SAFFRON is a single title, so I still need a way to eliminate the garbled fragment—either through OCR duplicate detection, a tighter threshold, or some other constraint.\n\nI'm considering a score-based approach: if one ALL_CAPS candidate scores significantly higher than the others, keep only that one. This would work for SAFFRON where the join should score much higher than the garbled fragment, but I need to be careful not to break FINNISH where both titles should score similarly and both should be kept. Maybe something like keeping the second title only if its score is at least 80% of the first title's score would work, though that's similar to the existing threshold logic.\n\nActually, I just realized something important about the existing pipeline. If Change 2 adds a structural heading bonus to the join, then the pre-filter at lines 344-352 should catch \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\" as a prefix and remove it. But \"FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)\" isn't a prefix of the join, so it won't be caught by that filter. The garbled fragment would only be removed if it fails the score threshold or gets caught by OCR duplicate detection.\n\nI think the best approach is to add targeted OCR duplicate detection specifically for ALL_CAPS candidates — checking if one has high word overlap with another and contains what looks like a truncated word. I'm writing the logic to iterate through pairs of all-caps candidates and identify which ones should be removed...\n\nImplementing OCR duplicate detection... Checking if non-shared words are truncations of longer words in the comparison text, and if so, marking the lower-scoring entry for removal since it's likely an OCR artifact. Looking at the SAFFRON example where \"FRON\" appears to be a truncation of \"SAFFRON\"... shared = [FINNISH, FLATBREADS] (2/3 = 67% > 50%)\n- nonShared = [MILK]\n- Is MILK a truncation of any bWord? FINNISH.includes(MILK)? No. POTATO.includes(MILK)? No. FLATBREADS.includes(MILK)? No.\n- allTruncated = false → don't remove\n- ✓\n\nThis approach correctly handles both cases. Now I need to finalize the improvement plan and double-check the separator format—the expected output uses \" : \" but the OCR data has \" / \", so I should account for that when comparing against results.txt.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3654,"cache_read_input_tokens":38679,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3654},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"78d44a45